76561198147876502,Recommended,272510,29109271,Posted: 7 January,all,DOC BLK JACK,EPIC XD
,Recommended,272510,12308429,"Posted: 30 September, 2014",all,Udkedae,"Naruto Shippuden: Ultimate Ninja Storm Revolution (that's a mouthful) is a great fighting game. The visuals in this series never disappoint, and the tweaks made to the gameplay make it a solid fighter with a bit of strategy set into it.(Please note that this doesn't cover all there is in the game. This is a review of what's important to note in the game)First off, the combat. The previous game in the series (Storm 3) had a great mechanic where your support would act according to the type you set for each one of them separately (auto, attack and defense). The possibilities back then were limited by your skill saving up chakra and attacking in coordination with your support characters to fill up the Storm Gauge. In Revolution they've changed it so you choose one single type of combat for your team. These types are broken into:Ultimate Jutsu Type:Allows you to perform an Ultimate Jutsu alone or in coordination with your 2 teammates if your Storm Gauge is filled to the top, however you can't access Awakening or make your teammates attack with you in a regular combo.Awakening Type:Allows you to access the Awakening state at any time during a fight and True Awakening given your Storm Gauge is filled up. The downside to this is you can't use Ultimate Jutsu and you still won't be able to use your teammates in a regular combo.Drive Type:Keeps your teammates with you at all times in three different forms: Auto Drive, Defense Drive and Attack Drive. Auto Drive makes your team attack with you during combos and deliver a final blow into your opponent by the end of a regular combo and often protect from Ultimate Jutsu aimed towards you, Defense Drive provides defense from your team when charging chakra or being approached with a Ninja or Chakra Dash, and Attack Drive works pretty much like Auto but without your team taking hits from Ultimate Jutsu for you. This type can’t use Ultimate Jutsu or Awakening mode.All three types can use Jutsu no matter the type and support during team battles.New to the series is a single player mode called Ultimate Ninja Tournament. In this mode you and 3 AI controlled opponents fight against each other in the same arena. It's a competition for orbs which are dropped each time a character takes a hit, this will decrease the amount of orbs held by the victim and increase the ones held by the attacker. There are no health bars in this mode but taking a hit when your orb count is at zero will leave you off the battle. The fighter with the most orbs at the end of each round wins. There are of course many hazards in these arena battles, on top of 3 enemies that could gang up on you at any given time.It's a fun mode that would replace the Story Mode in a numbered Ultimate Ninja Storm game, and while it's not story heavy every aspect of it nods towhat ifstories with lots of fan service content.Another interesting aspect to the game is the customization. Online Ninja Cards make a return for this entry but character customization is a most welcome add on to the game. You can choose up to 3 accessories to be place on your character's arms, face, back or waist, a substitution item to replace the generic log, and 1 of four Ultimate Jutsu Finish screens for each character. All of these items are unlockable through Ultimate Ninja Tournament mode and by fighting Network Clones online.The Ninja Escapades mode lets you play through short anime stories exclusive to the game. The little story they tell goes from gameplay to anime seamlessly, a nice touch that makes it enjoyable as short as it is.At the end of the day this game's perfect for those people who like the anime, games and wish to do some fighting online and/or locally, but if you're looking for an epic battle conclusion to the events after Storm 3 you're going to be disappointed (though the character's dialogues are set up to that point in the story arc, which could come as spoilers to those who haven't kept up with the series at some points).Pros:Massive character rosterDiverse customization optionsThe new combat allows you to truly see the type you chooseFan service all over the placeCons:The team types are great but not perfect. Some are unfair in the right hands.You can't put accessories on special outfits (Anbu, school, warrior, etc.)The story is there but you have to dig to find itHints:Learn the basic and new techniques before heading onlineMake sure you try every character to know what you're fighting againstNeverfight someone online if your connection is at 2 bars (let alone 1)After completing it to 100% I definitely recommend this game. The fan service, the visuals, the music, and the amount of content I did not include in this review make a solid game in the series, and a must if you can't wait for the next numbered entry."
