76561198046310643,Recommended,272510,12141335,"Posted: 18 September, 2014",all,Kalkiru,"Let me preface this by saying I have been playing this title largely on my PS3 (which is why my play time on the steam version is really low, don't worry I will definitely be fixing that).With that out of the way, lets get into the review. This game is a solid game and a decent addition to the storm series for a few reasons, though it is held back a little by lacking story content to a large degree. To be fair, there hasn't been much story progression from the anime/manga since storm 3, so I'm not really surprised to see them offer more filler based content in this iteration.The story content is based around 3 very short 'escapades' that involve some animation in-between battles, these backstories revolve around the Akatsuki, Itachi and Shisui Uchiha and Kakashi's former team mates when they were younger. There is also the Mecha-Naruto story line, although I wouldn't count that as much of a narrative, while funny and slightly heartwarming, its execution was a little lacking and isn't much of a story by itself.Beyond the lacking story content however is where we get to the meat of the game, and ultimately, the part where it shines the most. That would be the gameplay. While not too much of an overhaul, since this game runs on the same engine as the previous title, new battle mechanics as well as offering meaningful choice in how to play your characters really do add polish to the system.Within this new system, players are offered the choice of 3 different types of set up for any given character, these types are Ultimate Jutsu, Awakening and Drive. UJ allows your character to perform their ultimate jutsu, and when their storm bar is full (a new mechanic) they can peform a team ultimate jutsu that executes a combo before their UJ is done. The upside of picking this is that UJ is much easier to land when using all the members of your team as a proxy for the technique (if even one of the 3 characters connects in dash, the technique is cast). For the Awakening type, you can do just that, anyone picking this has access to both Instant Awakening and True Awakening. IA has its advantages for both comboing attacks and also adding strength to the fight when you need it (balanced by reducing max chakra, thereby making it impossible to awaken breifly after using IA). True Awakening if actually used in a fight adds a lot of extra power and in some characters cases an almost boss-like presence on the battefield while in this state, this is something that can really turn the fight around. Drive types revolve around teamwork and automatic support, in order to balance not having either IA/True Awakening or UJ/team UJ's anyone using this type can count on automatic support as well as switching support focus during battle, on top of this supports knocked out during the fight may revive after a period of time has passed. The drive type's only trump card is the ability to seal both UJ's and Awakening types abilities for a short period of time.Also of note, in this iteration of the storm series, customisation has been added, you can now edit your characters looks with accessories as well as their Substitution item and the video that plays upon a successful UJ finisher. Allowing both visual customisation, as well as focus choice really lets someone play how they would want to play, obviously its not the most in-depth customisation system, but it is a very welcome addition to the game.Adding to this is some new battle mechanics, along with the usual Sub/Guard defence, a counter mechanic and guard break attack have been added, these new mechanics are balanced by their use of resources (reduction of max chakra for counter and ammo system for guard break). With these, and all previous options from the last game, as well as character focus types, present a lot more depth within fights than was seen in storm 3. There are now few more options for both the defending and attacking player, which leads to more interesting fights overall.Of course, all of this is to speak nothing of the visuals of the game itself. It is quite a beautiful game, the style of the characters is very faithful to the animation style of the anime, and the environments to fight in are just as great to look at as the characters themselves. Add to this the technique animations, including the new awakenings/Special team ultimate jutsu's and this game certainly does not disappoint on the eye candy factor.I have very few issues with this game, but there were a few things to stick out. Firstly, while the ninja world tournament mode is great, and a fun diversion, the amount of redundant content is a bit too much. There are challanges and 'jobs' on top of recruitment quests for this mode, and while recruitment quests aren't all that bad, there are aLOTof jobs to be done. Case in point, there were at almost 20 jobs for each rank of the tournament I have been in so far, and a vast majority are just the standard 1v1 with supports or the 4v4 orb brawl mode with only one or two being anything different and all of these fights have no real story context. Add to this the challanges of each rank and you have a sizable list of content to get through. The trouble is that it all feels quite repetative after a while, leading to the realisation that the developer added these almost grind like elements mainly for the completionists and to give longevity to what would have otherwise been a short mode.All in all, here are the pros/cons for this game.Pros:New focus types/Customization add to personal choiceEnvironments and characters are as beautiful as everAwakening/UJ/Team UJ animations are awesomeNew fight mechanics on top of old help to make the fights more interesting than the last gameNaruto and Sasuke Swapping outfits had me fanboying a little, smart move CC2Shisui Uchiha and Kurama mode Naruto as playable characters? yesplsCons:Lack of longer story content could upset a few fansRedundant content in the Ninja tournament mode is a little annoyingWhile I enjoyed the Mecha-Naruto story somewhat, I can see why a lot of people couldn't take his addition to the game seriouslyDanzo existsIn summary, this game is better than storm 3, gameplay wise and I suppose graphics wise and is a solid title in itself, but the lack of story content may irk some fans (though it doesn't bother me to much) and the amount of redundant content in the nina world tournament mode may get on the nerves of some completionists.I give it, 7/10."
