76561198062262254,Not Recommended,272510,16658749,"Posted: 23 June, 2015",all,Ninjuh,"TL;DR: A lack of story mode and less-than-acceptable servers keep this release from greatness despite many gameplay improvements from storm 3. The naruto storm series from generations >> onwards shouldn't be overlooked or slept on because of percieved ""gimmicky"" combat centered around ninja movement and it's yearly releases.  The very mechanic of ninja movement/dashing contributes strongly to a solid fighting metagame centered around good spacing, timing, reading, baiting, bar observation etc.Keep in mind, as a yearly release this is a ""filler"" game. There is no story mode to be found here, this is made by a team of 170 otaku japs who're paid to produce this yearly; they create filler games like this and Generations in order to test new mechanics and smooth things out for the main releases. On that note, I have high hopes for storm 4 which will likely be worth buying as a naruto fan simply for the story mode gameplay just as Storm 3 was.This game is very enjoyable when learned and played with narutofriends irl. However, for this game in particular, if you're going to be playing online only you'll have a bad time due to sub-par servers and a lack of people playing with half-decent connections anymore. Because of this and a lack of story mode, I can't reccomend Revolution.For fans of the series, I would say Storm 2 and 3 are worth purchasing for the story as the cel-shaded animation is superb. The boss fights manage to capture the feel of the manga while, in my opinion, outdoing much of what studio Pierrot does in the anime.And something I feel needed to be addressed about this series for fighting fan critics, a defense of the combos: ""There's only 3 combos for each character"" is a very poor excuse to overlook this game as a fighter if you really enjoy them. Don't knock it before you try it, and I would reccomend looking at some of the higher-tier online gameplay videos to get a feel for how this can really be played. The 3-combo-system is also all centered around set up. Hit him onto the ground to keep him close, knock him back to gain some distance, throw him into the air to make him vulnerable. It's all about the movement.Also, many of the combos have some very tricky things throughout them.For example, some characters throw ranged weapons at specific points in their combo which can then be used to catch your opponent and rush in for a combo. In addition, each of those combos have particular moments within the moves which can be interrupted by ""rushing"" in at the intervals which may then be counter-countered by your opponent if they read your rush correctly.If you're really that critical, I would even reccomend simply pirating this game and playing it on single matches and then teams with a friend. You will more than likely start to see what you're missing."
